/purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe disintegration of Yugoslavia, accompanied by the emergence of new borders, is paradigmatically highlighting the relevance of borders in processes of societal change, crisis and conflict. This is even more the case, if we consider the violent practices that evolved out of populist discourse of ethnically homogenous bounded space in this process that happened in the wars in Yugoslavia in the 1990ies. Exploring the boundaries of Yugoslavia is not just relevant in the context of Balkan area studies, but the sketched phenomena acquire much wider importance, and can be helpful in order to better understand the dynamics of b/ordering societal space, that are so characteristic for our present situation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 4aBalkanhalbinsel. 4aGrenzen. 4aJugoslawien.  aB/ordering Processes, Spatializing and Imagining Borders, Balkans, Mobilities, Social Boundaries and Prejudice.1 aBešlin, Milivoj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDetchev, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolghin, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuančić, Vedran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFotiadis, Ruža, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMikša, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadović, Srdjan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadović, Srdjan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSekulić, Tatjana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStefanov, Nenad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStefanov, Nenad, eeditor